🐰 Keploy: 2026-06-22T12:14:38.020627457+05:30 	[31mERROR[0m	Time freezing could not be verified before replaying tests.
If your app is non-Go (Node / Python / Java / Ruby): Keploy auto-injects the LD_PRELOAD shim when --freezeTime is set. Just re-run the replay with --freezeTime — no Dockerfile change needed.

If your app is Go, pick the path that matches how you run the app:
  - Native (the binary runs directly on the runner, no Docker for the app):
      1. Patch the local Go toolchain once (idempotent — runs through GOROOT and adds the faketime stub):
           sudo /lib/keploy/go_freeze_time_$(uname -m | sed 's/x86_64/amd64/;s/aarch64/arm64/')
      2. Build a SEPARATE faketime binary — the prod path is NEVER overwritten (rebuilding the prod binary with -tags=faketime silently corrupts every future record run):
           go build -tags=faketime -o ./bin/server.replay ./cmd/server
      3. Re-run the replay pointing at the new binary:
           sudo -E keploy sandbox local replay --command "./bin/server.replay" --freezeTime
  - Docker (app boots via `docker compose up <svc>`): patch your Dockerfile per https://keploy.io/docs/keploy-cloud/time-freezing/#for-golanggo-applications-- — OR ideally use a separate `Dockerfile.keploy` so the prod Dockerfile stays clean.

If you genuinely don't need time-freezing, disable it with --freezeTime=false. Contact support if your app depends on time freezing but the above paths don't help.
